<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-476-315  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 476 315.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 2 1990 v4 n33 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>French firm to offer early video-compression board. (LumiereTechnology VideoCube) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rosenthal, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lumiere Technology (product introduction).andO;Product:   Lumiere Technology VideoCube (Graphics board) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Data CompressionVideo SystemsMultimedia TechnologyGraphics Boards-CardsTrade ShowsFrance.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve RosenthalandM;Paris -- One of the first Macintosh boards to offer hardware-based videocompression may come out of France.andP;  At the Apple Expo here late last month,Lumiere Technology displayed VideoCube, a prototype image-compression versionof its 24-bit color MCB Mini-Capture Board.andM;The new model is equipped with an on-board CL-550 compression chip fromC-Cube Microsystems Inc. of San Jose, Calif.andP;  The board occupies a singleNuBus slot and can acquire images from NTSC (National Television SystemCommittee), PAL (European) and SECAM (French) video sources.andP;  It works withall current Mac II models.andM;VideoCube can compress a typical 1-Mbyte color image down to 30 to 50 Kbytesand store it on disk in less than a second.andP;  Nearly 40 full-color images canbe placed on a single disk.andP;  Compression also cuts down transmission time ofimages over networks, the company said.andM;The compression scheme used on the board is compatible with JPEG, a proposedinternational standard from the Joint Photographic Experts Group forstill-image compression.andP;  Compressed images can be decompressed withVideoCube or with other JPEG-compliant software or hardware products.andM;Standard MCB features include image capture and overlay with genlocking, 2Mbytes of on-board RAM plus 32 Kbytes of ROM, and support for resolutionsranging from 640 by 480 pixels to 768 by 576 pixels.andM;The MCB series is now sold in France, several other European countries and inJapan.andP;  U.S.andP;  distribution is under consideration.andM;Due in December, VideoCube will sell for about $3,595 in France; without thechip-based compression, the price will be about $1,380.andM;Lumiere is at 30 Rue Barge, 75015 Paris, France; 1-40-56-97-13.andO;</TEXT></DOC>